The paper discusses a new satisfiability engine that aims to improve computational performance by exploiting the internal structure of problems. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, which often deals with optimization and search problems. Additionally, the paper discusses various representations of Boolean satisfiability problems, which could fall under the sub-categories of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO). The paper also discusses previous attempts to improve the performance of the Davis-Putnam-Logemann-Loveland algorithm, which is a common algorithm used in software engineering (cs.SE) and programming languages (cs.PL).
